{
  "texts": [
    "Issues with dataset selection among NS-TD algorithms were first introduced in DLBench (Shwartz-Ziv and Armon, 2022), which compared tree-based algorithms to recently proposed deep learning algorithms on 11 classification and regression datasets with 7,000 to 1,000,000 samples.",
    "These works found that XGBoost (Chen and Guestrin, 2016) outperformed more recent deep learning approaches (Popov et al, 2020; Arik and Pfister, 2021; Baosenguo, 2021; Katzir et al, 2021), when evaluated on their shared datasets.",
    "Hence, experimental results can easily be skewed by dataset selection.",
    "TabularBench (Grinsztajn et al, 2022) extended this analysis to SSL4NS-TD (Gorishniy et al, 2021; Somepalli et al, 2022) across 45 classification and regression task datasets with 3,000 to 10,000 samples.",
    "TabularBench revealed that tree-based models yield superior predictions more consistently with much less computational cost since both deep learning and SSL4NS-TD approaches suffer from oversmoothing tabular decision boundaries, noisy features, and misrepresenting non-rotation-invariant data."
  ]
}